{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "The RHIC BES program covers a wide range of baryon stopping, over an order of magnitude of net-proton yields at midrapidity [32,40].Figure 9 presents the net-proton yields at midrapidity in Au+Au collisions at √ s NN = 7.7 GeV to 200 GeV [44].",
    "For all centralities in heavy ion collisions, the midrapidity net-baryon density follows an exponential distribution with the variable y = y by cm, where y b is the beam rapidity, and y cm is the center-of-mass rapidity.",
    "This variable y is referred to as the \"rapidity loss\" which for the midrapidity protons produced in a collider experiment is equal to beam rapidity: y = y b as y cm = 0.",
    "A single collision energy there- fore gives rise to a single point in Fig. 9.",
    "The data points at each centrality can be fitted with an exponential function A exp (-B y)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "The RHIC BES program covers a wide range of baryon stopping, over an order of magnitude of net-proton yields at midrapidity [32,40].Figure 9 presents the net-proton yields at midrapidity in Au+Au collisions at √ s NN = 7.7 GeV to 200 GeV [44]."
  ]
